entries.meaning: Any of various asteroids or other echinoderms (not in fact fish) with usually five arms, many of which eat bivalves or corals by everting their stomach.
(obsolete) Any many-armed or tentacled sea invertebrate, whether cnidarian, echinoderm, or cephalopod.
examples: But the largest of the star-fish kind is that sea monster called kruken, kraken or krabben. [...] As this enormous sea-animal in all probability may be reckoned of the polype, or of the star-fish, kind, it seems that the parts which are seen rising at its pleasure, and are called arms, are properly the tentacula, or feeding instruments, called horns as well as arms.

entries.meaning: (slang) A woman (or, less commonly, a gay man) who reluctantly takes part in sexual intercourse, and lies on the back while spreading the limbs.
(vulgar, slang, usually in translations of Japanese pornography) The anus.

verbs.description: starfish (third-person singular simple present starfishes, present participle starfishing, simple past and past participle starfished)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To assume a splayed-out shape, like that of a starfish.
examples: "Oh you damn bastard, why won't you let anybody love you," and then, before I could stop her, she threw herself between us and the glowing suitcase, starfishing in the blaze of light as he blew up.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To form into a splayed-out shape, like that of a starfish.
